 Scholars explores an academic culture in which disciplines are vigorously isolated and then further divided into specialized fields, making for a heady mix of scholarly alienation and disciplinary territorialism, a wealth of specialized inquiry and a poverty of general discussion. This pattern, however, is not necessary and immutable; rather, it stems from decisions made a century ago, when the American university assumed its modern form. Damrosch traces the political and economic assumptions behind these decisions and reveals their persisting effects on academic structures despite dramatic changes in the larger society. We Scholars makes a compelling case for a scholarly community more reflective of and attuned to today's needs. The author's call for cooperation as the basis for intellectual endeavor, both within and outside the academy, will resonate for anyone concerned with the present complexities and future possibilities of academic work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEducation, Humanistic. 0aErziehung, Schul- und Bildungswesen. 0aExpertise. 0aIntellectual life. 0aIntellectuelen. 0aUniversität. 0aUniversiteiten. 0aUniversität. 4aEducation, Higher -- Aims and objectives -- United States. 4aEducation, Humanistic -- United States. 4aUnited States -- Intellectual life -- 20th century. 4aUniversities and colleges -- United States -- Departments. 4aUniversities and colleges -- United States -- Faculty. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Social Science eBook Packagez9783110353556oZDB-23-HCI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067443080840uht